description.plain:
Ebba Tove Elsa Nilsson, professionally known as Tove Lo (pronounced Too-veh-Lu), is a Swedish singer-songwriter born and raised in Djursholm, Sweden.

She first rose to prominence  for her single, “Habits (Stay High)“, which became a top ten hit in the U.S. a year after its 2013 release, a dark breakup anthem that generated such Internet buzz that it led to a deal with Universal. “Habits“ and its follow-up, “Out of Mind“, appeared on her debut EP Truth Serum, in 2014.

Later that year, her debut album, Queen of the Clouds, arrived, featuring “Habits“. The album was a Top 10 hit in Sweden and a Top 20 hit in the U.S. and U.K., and the subsequent single “Talking Body“ was a similar success.

She returned in 2016 with her second album, Lady Wood, which delivered more of her signature mix of cool synth-pop and frank lyrics. Buoyed by the singles “Cool Girl“ and “True Disaster“, the album hit number 1 in Sweden, and landed at number 11 on the U.S. Billboard 200.

In 2017, Tove Lo  released her third album, BLUE LIPS (lady wood phase II), a companion piece to Lady Wood that featured the single “disco tits“.

In September 2019, she released her fourth album, *Sunshine Kitty, featuring collaborations with Kylie Minogue, ALMA, and Doja Cat.

Her nickname comes from a lynx (“Lo” in Swedish) she couldn’t stop staring at:

Three years old, I was standing with my face pressed against the glass,“ she recalls. "I didn’t want to leave. So my parents started calling me Tove Lo and it stuck.

Nilsson’s stage name is usually mispronounced Tōv Lō by her non-Swedish speaking fans. “For the record, it’s pronounced "Too-veh Lu” but Tove doesn’t mind if people approach it phonetically."

songs.full_title: Habits (Stay High) by Tove Lo
songs.title: Habits (Stay High)

description.plain:
The narrator of “Habits (Stay High)” describes engaging in some unhealthy behavior as a means to cope with the pain of a break-up. We should ask “Is the narrator Tove Lo or a fictional character?”.  In this interview, Lo describes the song, saying “it is about one relationship … very honest” and “It is all inspired about that [relationship] really … and me being very open about my mistakes.”.  She also says that she writes all of the lyrics herself and “When I write for myself, it is always going to be my life and my experiences.  It is going to be very unfiltered, and I am not gonna try and censor myself.”.  In this interview, she is asked

A ton of people do drugs, but don’t necessarily admit to it. There’s definitely a taboo about actually admitting to doing them, versus what everyone does behind closed doors. So the fact that you were open about that, some people might consider that a bit controversial.

and responds

That’s true. Well, it’s way easier for me to sing about things than to talk about things. I’ll say something in a song, and then people will confront me about it. I’ll be like, ‘Well, just listen to the song,’ because it is harder for me to talk about it. All I can say is that I’m always going to be honest and upfront in my music. Some people are going to be offended and some people are going to relate, and I think that’s just how it’s going to be.

Based on the interviews, the song seems autobiographical and the narrator is Lo.  On the other hand in interviews Lo is careful to avoid making clear factual statements about using illegal drugs, going to sex clubs, and picking up daddies at the playground. One can still argue that while the song is “honest” about her emotional experiences, it could contain some exaggerations in some of its facts.

songs.title: Talking Body

description.plain:
“Talking Body” subtly bemoans an overly casual approach to sex. According to Tove Lo:

It’s about two people trying to get over their problems by having lots and lots of sex.

It was the third single from her debut album, following up international hit “Habits (Stay High)” and “Not On Drugs,” hitting the Top 40 in the US and Canada.

For reference, Tove Lo’s body is 5'6 and somewhere around 130 pounds. The model who stars in this song’s video, Filip Roséen, is listed as 6'2.

Check out how much this mega-hit changed from the original demo:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=4&v=_8lFVDt_bjk

songs.full_title: Cool Girl by Tove Lo
songs.title: Cool Girl

description.plain:
“"Cool Girl” is an electropop song written by Tove Lo, Ludvig Söderberg, and Jakob Jerlström, with its production handled by the latter two as the production duo The Struts. Lyrically, the song is about an invitation to form a non-traditional and non-monogamous romance, in which the singer describes herself as a “cool girl” interested in an open relationship. According to Lo, the song’s main lyrical theme was inspired by a scene and monologue from the feature film Gone Girl (2014), where the character of Amy Elliott-Dunne (portrayed by Rosamund Pike) “goes from being a victim to a psycho.”

The track comes after she told Fuse at the 2016 Billboard Music Awards that she had finished recording her new album and described it as:

There’s definitely a different sound to it — we’ve gone a little bit more dark techno vibe with it, some of it. You know, blended with pop.

Lorde has expressed her excitement for the track tweeting:
https://twitter.com/lorde/status/760649968898101248

Tove uploaded various teasers onto social media prior to the release of the track.
